      Bill Ackman vs. Harvard
   =20
 =20

One model of a=C2=A0charitable endowment is that you are in the business of=
 selling appreciated assets on behalf of your donors in order to maximize t=
ax efficiency. Like:
=09A rich person owns some stock. She bought it for, say, $1 million, and i=
t is worth $10 million now.=09She could sell the stock for $10 million, pay=
 taxes on her gains, and be left with something like $8 million.
  [1]
=C2=A0She could then donate that money to you and deduct $8 million from he=
r income taxes for the year, saving $3 million or so.
  [2]

=09
Or she could=C2=A0give=C2=A0you the stock. Then she would not recognize any=
 gains on the sale, and she=E2=80=99d get to deduct its full market value f=
rom her income taxes, saving almost $4 million. You get a bigger gift ($10 =
million instead of $8 million), and she gets a bigger tax deduction. Better=
 trade!=09Then=C2=A0you=C2=A0sell the stock, for $10 million, and don=E2=80=
=99t pay any taxes, because you are a non-taxable charitable endowment.

This is a very well-known feature of US tax law; wealth managers will commo=
nly=C2=A0tell you to donate appreciated stock rather than cash, and if you =
go to, like, Harvard University=E2=80=99s web page, they will tell you how =
to donate stock, because it comes up a lot.
In this process, Step 4 is not strictly essential. If you are a big charita=
ble endowment, you are not spending all of your money every year. You are i=
nvesting it for the long run. Maybe you want to keep this stock; maybe you =
think it has room to run and will be worth more in the long run.=C2=A0
But if you are a big charitable endowment, you have some=C2=A0plan. You sit=
 down and think about how to construct your portfolio; you say =E2=80=9Cwe =
should be 50% stocks and 5% bonds and 15% hedge funds and 20% private equit=
y and 10% timberland=E2=80=9D or whatever, and then you pick assets and man=
agers within each category to get the portfolio that you think will best po=
sition you for the long run. And then if some big donor comes in and gives =
you $10 million in cash, you allocate it to that portfolio.
But lots of donors instead come to you with stock that has appreciated a lo=
t (often stock in their own companies), they want to maximize their gifts a=
nd their deductions, and they know that the way to do that is by donating t=
he stock. The stock doesn=E2=80=99t fit with your plan. You are not making =
an=C2=A0investment decision=C2=A0each time they donate the stock. You are, =
several times a year, getting a big concentrated position in some random st=
ock that your big donors happen to own. An endowment with an investment por=
tfolio consisting only of the stuff that its donors happened to have lying =
around would look crazy. You take the random stuff, you sell it, you buy in=
dex funds or timberland or whatever.
You are essentially a middleman: You have some target portfolio of assets y=
ou want to own, but your donations come largely in the form of=C2=A0other=
=C2=A0assets that your donors happen to own, and you are in a position to e=
fficiently turn the donated assets into the target assets.=C2=A0
This can lead to occasional problems, though:
=09Your donors are often able to give all that money because they are succe=
ssful investors, and they=C2=A0like=C2=A0the stock they gave you. They thin=
k it has room to run. If you dump it the second they donate it, they will b=
e offended. If you are like =E2=80=9Cno, you don=E2=80=99t understand, we d=
ump=C2=A0all=C2=A0the random stuff that donors give us, we have our own inv=
estment thesis and don=E2=80=99t want to just own your hand-me-downs,=E2=80=
=9D they will be even more offended. =E2=80=9CRandom stuff!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
=09Your donors are often in position to give all that money because they ar=
e=C2=A0good=C2=A0investors, and often they are=C2=A0right, and the stock=C2=
=A0does=C2=A0go up much more than your timberland or whatever, and then you=
 look dumb in hindsight.

Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Pierre Paulden reports:=C2=A0

Bill Ackman=C2=A0denied that his weeks-long crusade against=C2=A0Harvard Un=
iversity=C2=A0and its president was driven by resentment toward his alma ma=
ter, but acknowledged a =E2=80=9Cserious=E2=80=9D dispute with the school o=
ver a donation he made in 2017.
=E2=80=9CTo be extremely clear, my advocacy on behalf of antisemitism, free=
 speech on campus, and my concerns with DEI at Harvard have absolutely noth=
ing to do with my unfortunate experience as a donor to the university,=E2=
=80=9D Ackman wrote in a post on X Tuesday night.

In 2017, Ackman wanted to give Harvard money to recruit economist Raj Chett=
y, but he =E2=80=9Chad no liquidity=E2=80=9D due to a divorce. So:

Ackman=E2=80=99s solution was to give Harvard stock in=C2=A0Coupang Inc., a=
t the time a speculative private venture-backed company.
The stock he was giving was valued at $10 million, but Ackman said he agree=
d with Harvard that if the value went below $10 million he would make up th=
e difference. But if the company went public and the stock was worth more t=
han $15 million, he would have the right =E2=80=9Cto allocate the excess re=
alized value=E2=80=9D above that amount to any Harvard-related initiative o=
f his choice.

From Ackman=E2=80=99s long tweet on the matter:
In Wall Street speak, Harvard had a put to me at $10m, and I retained a cal=
l at $15m, with the right to allocate the excess value to the Harvard initi=
ative of my choice.
In 2021, Coupang   went public, and the shares he gave to Harvard were wort=
h $85 million. He called Harvard with the good news, only to find out that =
Harvard had already dumped the stock. Paulden:
He was informed that Harvard Management Co., which oversees the $51 billion=
 endowment, had sold the stock back to Coupang in a private transaction in =
March 2020. Ackman said no one from Harvard Management or the administratio=
n contacted him at the time to ask if he wanted to buy back the stock or to=
 apologize after the fact for missing out on $75 million of potential gains=
.
Apparently the sale price was $10 million, the same as the valuation when h=
e gave it. Ackman argues that this was a bad investing decision by Harvard:

Harvard had sold stock which it could have put to me for $10m at a massive =
discount to its value at that time. Coupang had made massive progress since=
 my gift in December 2017 and the stock's value had increased enormously. =
=C2=A0
And Harvard had never told me that they had sold the shares.=C2=A0I was nev=
er offered the opportunity to buy the shares back for $10m or a higher pric=
e, which I would happily have done, had I known the University needed liqui=
dity. =C2=A0
And the notion that Harvard needed $10m of liquidity in the context of a $5=
0 billion endowment is on its face absurd. Any sophisticated investor shoul=
d also understand that when a private venture-backed company is buying back=
 stock, it is a bad idea to sell.
Harvard sold the stock despite the fact that we had a contract which provid=
ed the University with downside protection at $10m while allowing it to ret=
ain 100% of the upside. It made no economic sense whatsoever for Harvard to=
 have sold.

And, sure, I suppose that=E2=80=99s right. Selling at $10 million when you =
have a put from Ackman at $10 million does extinguish a lot of option value=
; better to keep the stock,=C2=A0let it ride, and have some chance of getti=
ng $85 million with insurance that you won=E2=80=99t get less than $10 mill=
ion.
  [3]
=C2=A0And sure, arguably, it would have been polite (and a good financial m=
ove) for Harvard=E2=80=99s Portfolio Manager For Bill Ackman to call him to=
 be like =E2=80=9Chey we are reshuffling the Bill Ackman Portfolio, do you =
want to buy any of it?=E2=80=9D I just don=E2=80=99t think that Harvard rea=
lly has a Portfolio Manager For Bill Ackman, and I think that its decision =
process is often less =E2=80=9Cdoes it make economic sense to sell this con=
centrated stock position that someone walked in and handed to us=E2=80=9D a=
nd more =E2=80=9Cwhy=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0we sell this stuff and inve=
st the money in something we picked?=E2=80=9D
Still there is also Ackman=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccall right,=E2=80=9D which is=
 a little odd: Did he have the right to allocate the excess above $15 milli=
on=C2=A0if Harvard kept the stock and realized that excess, or was it just =
a standalone derivative contract where Harvard owed him any value of Coupan=
g over $15 million whether or not it owned the stock? The latter seems weir=
d, but Ackman seems to think that was the spirit of the deal; he writes:

Unfortunately, the stock sale issue has never been resolved and nearly thre=
e years have gone by. And it should not have been hard for Harvard to resol=
ve this problem. All Harvard has to do is honor the agreement it had made w=
ith me.=C2=A0That is, to grant me the right I bargained for:
The right to allocate the $70m of excess proceeds to the Harvard-related in=
itiative of my choice. =C2=A0
And this should not be hard. Harvard has $50,000,000,000 of assets, and Har=
vard's obligation to me represents only 0.14% of these funds, and the funds=
 all stay at Harvard. =C2=A0

Put his name on a program in nonprofit portfolio management.

