   =20
      Ross Stevens vs. Penn
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s a trade:
=09You are the founder, chief executive officer and main owner of some priv=
ate company. Say it=E2=80=99s worth $1 billion and you own 90%; your employ=
ees own the other 10%.=09You would like to make a charitable donation, say =
to your alma mater. Instead of giving cash, you give some of the shares tha=
t you own in your company. Say you give the charity 10% of the company, wor=
th $100 million. Now you own 80%, the charity owns 10%, your employees own =
10%.=09You take a $100=C2=A0million tax deduction, on your personal taxes: =
You gave the charity property worth $100 million, so you deduct that from y=
our income for this year. That saves you, like,  $37=C2=A0million in taxes.=
=09A week=C2=A0later, you change your mind. But the gift is already final.=
=09But! Your=C2=A0company=C2=A0has an interesting corporate charter. Until =
last week, the only owners of the company were you and your employees. What=
 if they do something scandalous and you have to fire=C2=A0them? The compan=
y=E2=80=99s charter anticipates that possibility: It says that, if an emplo=
yee is fired for cause =E2=80=94=C2=A0for breaking the law, for bringing di=
sgrace on the company, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then their shares are forfeited.=
 They just disappear: They don=E2=80=99t get paid out for those shares, the=
y just lose them, and everyone else owns a bit more of the company.=09What =
if you can fire the charity for cause? What if your alma mater did somethin=
g scandalous? Then you can take away their shares without paying them. The =
$100 million stake that the charity owned in your company just vanishes.=09=
Because the charity=E2=80=99s 10% stake is canceled, you now own 88.9% of t=
he company, and your employees own 11.1%.
  [4]

=09But what about taxes?=09Arguably, by canceling the charity=E2=80=99s sha=
re of the company and effectively reallocating it (mostly) to yourself (and=
 a little to your employees), you have income: The value of your stake in t=
he company increased by about $89 million, so you have $89 million of taxab=
le income. (And your employees have $11 million of taxable income, whoops.
  [5]
)=09But=C2=A0arguably=C2=A0there is no income. After all, you haven=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0gotten more shares:=C2=A0All that is happened is that some=C2=A0o=
ther owner=E2=80=99s shares were canceled. If I own stock in Amazon.com Inc=
., and Amazon buys back somebody else=E2=80=99s stock, my ownership interes=
t in Amazon goes up, but I don=E2=80=99t report income or pay taxes. (If I =
donate $1 million of corporate stock to charity in 2023, and in 2024 the co=
mpany goes bankrupt and the shares become worthless, I still keep the 2023 =
tax deduction.) Arguably something similar happened here: Someone else=E2=
=80=99s shares were canceled, but you didn=E2=80=99t get any more shares, s=
o you have no income, so you don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes.=09So you donated =
$100 million of stock (Step 2), got a tax deduction worth $37 million (Step=
 3), got=C2=A0back=C2=A0$89 million of stock (Step 7), and kept the tax ded=
uction (Step 10). You are up $26 million. Good trade!=09Such a good trade t=
hat you might go out and find some=C2=A0other=C2=A0charities to give money =
to, charities that you think might=C2=A0also=C2=A0disappoint you, so you ca=
n do this again.

I=E2=80=99m kidding, I think. I don=E2=80=99t think this trade actually wor=
ks, or that anyone would do it. But having spotted a funny possible tax she=
lter, I feel obligated to mention it to you, though I feel far more obligat=
ed to tell you that (1) it is not legal or tax advice and (2) in fact a tax=
 lawyer I talked to was like =E2=80=9Cnah I don=E2=80=99t think so.=E2=80=
=9D
  [6]
 Still here=E2=80=99s this:

A University of Pennsylvania donor is withdrawing a gift worth around $100 =
million to protest the school's response to antisemitism on campus.
The big picture: The final straw for Ross Stevens, founder and CEO of Stone=
 Ridge Asset Management, was Tuesday's widely criticized congressional test=
imony by Penn president Liz Magill.
Details: The gift from Stevens, a Penn undergrad alum, was given in Decembe=
r 2017 to help establish a center for innovation in finance.
It was in the form of limited partnership units in Stone Ridge, with the cu=
rrent value estimated at around $100 million.
Stevens, in a letter from his lawyers to Penn, alleges that the school has =
violated the terms of the limited partnership agreement, including its anti=
-discrimination and anti-harassment policies.

That=E2=80=99s from Axios=E2=80=99s Dan Primack last Thursday; since then, =
Magill has resigned and maybe Stevens is appeased. I have no idea if he act=
ually withdrew the gift,=C2=A0or will do it. But the bones of the trade are=
 there. He is the founder and controlling owner of Stone Ridge Holdings Gro=
up LP, which owns Stone Ridge Asset Management and a few related financial =
businesses. He donated some Stone Ridge limited partnership units to Penn; =
those units are =E2=80=9Cnow valued at approximately $100 million,=E2=80=9D=
 Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s lawyers say in a letter to Penn that Primack include=
d with his story.
And then, well,=C2=A0Stevens=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t ask for the units back; ra=
ther,=C2=A0Stone Ridge=C2=A0threatened to cancel them. The lawyers represen=
t the firm, not Stevens himself. They write:

As a holder of Stone Ridge Unit, the University is bound by and must comply=
 with the terms of Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s limited partner agreement (=E2=80=
=98LP Agreement=E2=80=99). Under that Agreement, Stone Ridge has the abilit=
y, in its sole discretion, to retire the Units of a limited partner that ha=
s engaged in conduct constituting =E2=80=9CLimited Partner Cause.=E2=80=9D =
(LP Agreement =C2=A7 10.12.) The LP Agreement defines =E2=80=9CLimited Part=
ner Cause=E2=80=9D broadly to include, as relevant here, violations (by the=
 limited partner) of laws or rules applicable to Stone Ridge that are "mate=
rially injurious to [Stone Ridge's] business, reputation, character or stan=
ding.=E2=80=9D (Id. =C2=A7 2.1.)
Among the rules applicable to Stone Ridge are its own anti-discrimination a=
nd anti-harassment policies and the laws=C2=A0of New York State that prohib=
it workplace discrimination and harassment. For example, Stone Ridge strict=
 prohibits all forms of discrimination and harassment based on, among other=
 things, religion. =E2=80=9CThis prohibition applies to physical conduct, v=
erbal conduct (including taunting,=C2=A0jokes, threats, epithets, derogator=
y comments or slurs based on an individual's protected status);=C2=A0and vi=
sual and/or written conduct {including derogatory posters. photographs, cal=
endars, cartoons, drawings, websites, email, text messages or gestures base=
d on an indvidual=E2=80=99s protected status). These policies, among others=
, were enacted by Stone Ridge to ensure a safe and respectful environment o=
r its employees.
Mr. Stevens and Stone Ridge are appalled by the University=E2=80=99s stance=
 on antisemitism on campus. Its permissive approach to hate speech calling =
for violence against Jews and laissez faire attitude toward harassment and =
discrimination against Jewish students would violate any policies of rules =
that prohibit harassment and discrimination based on religion, including th=
ose of Stone Ridge. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In light of the foregoing, Stone Ridge h=
as reason to believe that the University=E2=80=99s actions (or lack thereof=
) constitute =E2=80=9CLimited Partner Cause=E2=80=9D under Section 10.12 of=
 the LP Agreement, which gives Stone Ridge the ability, in its sole discret=
ion, to retire the University=E2=80=99s Units.

This is an incredibly weird argument. The idea of that =E2=80=9CLimited Par=
tner Cause=E2=80=9D provision is surely, like, if one of the employee-owner=
s of Stone Ridge does sexual harassment and embarrasses the firm, he can be=
 fired and his units confiscated. It is harder to see how Penn violated any=
 =E2=80=9Claws or rules applicable to Stone Ridge,=E2=80=9D or could possib=
ly have done so, or could possibly do something =E2=80=9Cmaterially injurio=
us to [Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s] business, reputation, character or standing.=
=E2=80=9D I assume the point here is to make a clever threat, not an argume=
nt that could stand up in court.
But never mind that! My point is just that when Stevens donated the units, =
he presumably could have taken a tax deduction, but if=C2=A0Stone Ridge=C2=
=A0takes them back, he maybe doesn=E2=80=99t need to reverse that deduction=
? Cool trade if so.

 =20
   =20
      Lawyer AI
   =20
 =20

I   wrote yesterday about how deals are typically negotiated by arguing abo=
ut what terms are =E2=80=9Cmarket,=E2=80=9D that is, standard in deals of t=
hat type. One question is how you know what terms are market. I said:
You have to pay attention to what deals happen, and have someone summarize =
them, but with a bit of work you can build a database, or even keep running=
 track of all the deals in your head I guess.=C2=A0Or get yourself a large =
language model and ask it =E2=80=9Cwhat is a standard ordinary course of bu=
siness covenant for a US public company merger these days?=E2=80=9D
Coincidentally also yesterday Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Brian Baxter   wrote abou=
t an AI-for-lawyers startup that wants to do that:

Noetica AI, a startup software platform headed by a former Wachtell, Lipton=
, Rosen & Katz associate, announced Tuesday a $6 million seed investment ro=
und led by venture capital firm Lightspeed Venture Partners. =E2=80=A6
The technology is still not a =E2=80=9Csilver bullet,=E2=80=9D though if us=
ed properly, artificial intelligence can be for lawyers what Microsoft Exce=
l was to investment bankers, said Daniel Wertman, Noetica AI=E2=80=99s chie=
f executive officer, who until last year was a corporate finance associate =
at Wachtell. =E2=80=A6
He said he was sitting at his desk at Wachtell one day and asked a senior l=
awyer how to access a market database to check if a borrower of a certain t=
ype could get specific terms. The answer? It didn=E2=80=99t exist.

I feel like a lot of junior lawyers have had that experience. Lawyers are t=
raditionally=C2=A0enemies of databases.
  [7]
=C2=A0The only way to get that database, at a law firm, is to have a robot =
build it for you.

