  [1] That=E2=80=99s $9 million of gains times a top federal capital gains =
rate of 20% is $1.8 million of taxes, leaving her with a bit more than $8 m=
illion, but then there=E2=80=99s state tax etc.


  [2] That is, $8 million times the top federal income tax rate of 37% is a=
bout $3 million.


  [3] I could argue this the other way. What is Ackman=E2=80=99s put worth?=
 Well, let=E2=80=99s say you=E2=80=99re Harvard, you have this Coupang stoc=
k, Ackman has promised to pay you the difference if it goes below $10 milli=
on, and it goes to $0 =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s a startup, startups commonly f=
ail, etc. You go to Ackman for the $10 million. One possibility is that he =
doesn=E2=80=99t have it: Whatever wiped out the value of Coupang also wiped=
 out his fortune, leaving him too strapped to give you the $10 million. Thi=
s doesn=E2=80=99t seem that likely, but it's not a zero probability. Anothe=
r possibility is that he doesn=E2=80=99t want to give it: Between his donat=
ion and Coupang=E2=80=99s fall, he has gotten mad at Harvard for some reaso=
n, and no longer wants to make up the shortfall. This has a higher probabil=
ity! Ackman does have some problems with Harvard! (In either of these two c=
ases, maybe you can sue him to enforce your arrangement, but that is a bad =
look and I don=E2=80=99t know how enforceable it is.) A third possibility i=
s that he writes you the $10 million check, but in his own mind he deducts =
that $10 million from what he would have given to Harvard anyway. You come =
to him at the end of the year saying =E2=80=9CHarvard could use an internat=
ional airport, could you chip in $10 million=E2=80=9D and he says =E2=80=9C=
what, no, I already wrote you a $10 million check this year, go away.=E2=80=
=9D The $10 million is not necessarily *additive*. So you would not, ex ant=
e, value this put at its full Black-Scholes value; you would not be absolut=
ely certain that the stock plus the put will always be worth at least $10 m=
illion.


  [4] That is, before, you owned 80 units, the charity owned 10, the employ=
ees owned 10. Now the charity=E2=80=99s 10 units are canceled, so you own 8=
0 out of 90 units, and the employees own 10 out of 90. This is not the only=
 way this contract could work, and my understanding is that it is more comm=
on, in an investment firm's limited partnership agreement, for canceled sha=
res to essentially be reallocated to the founder/CEO, meaning that in pract=
ice you=E2=80=99d end up back with 90% and the employees with 10%. But this=
 mechanism is theoretically possible, and funnier.


  [5] Again, this leakage is not necessary, or even common (see previous fo=
otnote); you might just get all $100 million of the value.


  [6] But with some doubt! Also, to be clear, I think the trade is pretty t=
ricky if your company is a *partnership*, as Stone Ridge is. Then the reall=
ocation of capital caused by the cancelation of another partner=E2=80=99s s=
hares arguably is income to you. (The relevant case is Lehman v. Commission=
er.) But I think that if your company is a *corporation* you are in better =
shape; canceling shares of a corporation clearly *isn=E2=80=99t* income to =
the other shareholders. I think it is less common for a corporation to have=
 a cancelation-of-shares-for-cause provision, though not theoretically impo=
ssible, and I think there are other tax reasons why you wouldn=E2=80=99t wa=
nt the company to be organized as a corporation, but still there=E2=80=99s =
maybe a fun trade there. This is incredibly not tax or legal advice.


  [7] Like, Microsoft Excel could be for lawyers what Microsoft Excel was t=
o investment bankers: When I was an investment banker, we *did* keep track =
of legal terms in an Excel spreadsheet, so we knew what was market. But tha=
t required someone to input each deal into the spreadsheet, and what lawyer=
 would do that?


