<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One model of a=C2=A0charitable endowment is th=
at you are in the business of selling appreciated assets on behalf of your =
donors in order to maximize tax efficiency. Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A rich person owns some stock. She bo=
ught it for, say, $1 million, and it is worth $10 million now.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">She could sell the stock for $10 million, pay =
taxes on her gains, and be left with something like $8 million.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0She could then donate that money to you and deduct $8 million fro=
m her income taxes for the year, saving $3 million or so.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Or </em>she could=C2=A0<em>give=C2=A0</em>you the stock. Then she would=
 not recognize any gains on the sale, and she=E2=80=99d get to deduct its f=
ull market value from her income taxes, saving almost $4 million. You get a=
 bigger gift ($10 million instead of $8 million), and she gets a bigger tax=
 deduction. Better trade!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then=C2=
=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>sell the stock, for $10 million, and don=E2=80=99t pay=
 any taxes, because you are a non-taxable charitable endowment.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a very well-known feature of US tax la=
w; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258399=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlkZWxpdHljaGFyaXRhYmxlLm9yZy9naXZpbmctYWNjb3VudC93aGF0LX=
lvdS1jYW4tZG9uYXRlL2RvbmF0aW5nLXN0b2NrLXRvLWNoYXJpdHktYjExMjMuaHRtbA/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBd687880e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wealth managers</a> will commonly=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258399=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Nod2FiLmNvbS9sZWFybi9zdG9yeS9pcy1pdC1iZXR0ZXItdG8tZ2l2ZS=
1zdG9jay1vci1jYXNoLXRvLWNoYXJpdHk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc214b288" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">tell you</a> to donate appreciated stock rather than cash, and if you go =
to, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779=
.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbHVtbmkuaGFydmFyZC5lZHUvZ2l2aW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB090b988f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Harvard University=E2=80=99s web page</a>, they will t=
ell you how to donate stock, because it comes up a lot.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In this process, Step 4 is not strictly essent=
ial. If you are a big charitable endowment, you are not spending all of you=
r money every year. You are investing it for the long run. Maybe you want t=
o keep this stock; maybe you think it has room to run and will be worth mor=
e in the long run.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you are a big charitable endowment, you=
 have some=C2=A0<em>plan</em>. You sit down and think about how to construc=
t your portfolio; you say =E2=80=9Cwe should be 50% stocks and 5% bonds and=
 15% hedge funds and 20% private equity and 10% timberland=E2=80=9D or what=
ever, and then you pick assets and managers within each category to get the=
 portfolio that you think will best position you for the long run. And then=
 if some big donor comes in and gives you $10 million in cash, you allocate=
 it to that portfolio.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But lots of donors instead come to you with st=
ock that has appreciated a lot (often stock in their own companies), they w=
ant to maximize their gifts and their deductions, and they know that the wa=
y to do that is by donating the stock. The stock doesn=E2=80=99t fit with y=
our plan. You are not making an=C2=A0<em>investment decision=C2=A0</em>each=
 time they donate the stock. You are, several times a year, getting a big c=
oncentrated position in some random stock that your big donors happen to ow=
n. An endowment with an investment portfolio consisting only of the stuff t=
hat its donors happened to have lying around would look crazy. You take the=
 random stuff, you sell it, you buy index funds or timberland or whatever.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You are essentially a middleman: You have some=
 target portfolio of assets you want to own, but your donations come largel=
y in the form of=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>assets that your donors happen to=
 own, and you are in a position to efficiently turn the donated assets into=
 the target assets.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This can lead to occasional problems, though:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your donors are often able to give al=
l that money because they are successful investors, and they=C2=A0<em>like=
=C2=A0</em>the stock they gave you. They think it has room to run. If you d=
ump it the second they donate it, they will be offended. If you are like =
=E2=80=9Cno, you don=E2=80=99t understand, we dump=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>t=
he random stuff that donors give us, we have our own investment thesis and =
don=E2=80=99t want to just own your hand-me-downs,=E2=80=9D they will be ev=
en more offended. =E2=80=9CRandom stuff!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your donors are often in position to give all that mo=
ney because they are=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>investors, and often they are=
=C2=A0<em>right</em>, and the stock=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>go up much more=
 than your timberland or whatever, and then you look dumb in hindsight.</li=
>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMTMvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tc2F5cy1oYXJ2YXJkLXN=
xdWFuZGVyZWQtZ2lmdC1idXQtZGVuaWVzLXJlc2VudG1lbnQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxMzIzX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jMxMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e89886f" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Pierre Paulden reports</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bill Ackman=C2=A0denied that his weeks-long cr=
usade against=C2=A0Harvard University=C2=A0and its president was driven by =
resentment toward his alma mater, but acknowledged a =E2=80=9Cserious=E2=80=
=9D dispute with the school over a donation he made in 2017.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CTo be extremely clear, my advocacy on=
 behalf of antisemitism, free speech on campus, and my concerns with DEI at=
 Harvard have absolutely nothing to do with my unfortunate experience as a =
donor to the university,=E2=80=9D Ackman wrote in a post on X Tuesday night=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2017, Ackman wanted to give Harvard money t=
o recruit economist Raj Chetty, but he =E2=80=9Chad no liquidity=E2=80=9D d=
ue to a divorce. So:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ackman=E2=80=99s solution was to give Harvard =
stock in=C2=A0Coupang Inc., at the time a speculative private venture-backe=
d company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stock he was giving was valued at $10 mill=
ion, but Ackman said he agreed with Harvard that if the value went below $1=
0 million he would make up the difference. But if the company went public a=
nd the stock was worth more than $15 million, he would have the right =E2=
=80=9Cto allocate the excess realized value=E2=80=9D above that amount to a=
ny Harvard-related initiative of his choice.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From Ackman=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS=
9CaWxsQWNrbWFuL3N0YXR1cy8xNzM0NzE1MTM1Njc4MTc3NDE5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bb24e6c8f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">long tweet</a> on the matter:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Wall Street speak, Harvard had =
a put to me at $10m, and I retained a call at $15m, with the right to alloc=
ate the excess value to the Harvard initiative of my choice.</p></blockquot=
e>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, Coupang <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTYvY291cGFuZy1zLWlwby1wb3Atc2VydmVkLW=
EtcHVycG9zZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfbd6157b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  went public</a>, and the s=
hares he gave to Harvard were worth $85 million. He called Harvard with the=
 good news, only to find out that Harvard had already dumped the stock. Pau=
lden:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He was informed that Harvard Manag=
ement Co., which oversees the $51 billion endowment, had sold the stock bac=
k to Coupang in a private transaction in March 2020. Ackman said no one fro=
m Harvard Management or the administration contacted him at the time to ask=
 if he wanted to buy back the stock or to apologize after the fact for miss=
ing out on $75 million of potential gains.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apparently the sale price was $10 million, the=
 same as the valuation when he gave it. Ackman argues that this was a bad i=
nvesting decision by Harvard:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Harvard had sold stock which it could have put=
 to me for $10m at a massive discount to its value at that time. Coupang ha=
d made massive progress since my gift in December 2017 and the stock's valu=
e had increased enormously. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Harvard had never told me that they had so=
ld the shares.=C2=A0I was never offered the opportunity to buy the shares b=
ack for $10m or a higher price, which I would happily have done, had I know=
n the University needed liquidity. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the notion that Harvard needed $10m of liq=
uidity in the context of a $50 billion endowment is on its face absurd. Any=
 sophisticated investor should also understand that when a private venture-=
backed company is buying back stock, it is a bad idea to sell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Harvard sold the stock despite the fact that w=
e had a contract which provided the University with downside protection at =
$10m while allowing it to retain 100% of the upside. It made no economic se=
nse whatsoever for Harvard to have sold.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, sure, I suppose that=E2=80=99s right. Sel=
ling at $10 million when you have a put from Ackman at $10 million does ext=
inguish a lot of option value; better to keep the stock,=C2=A0let it ride, =
and have some chance of getting $85 million with insurance that you won=E2=
=80=99t get less than $10 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And sure, arguably, it would have been polite (and a good financi=
al move) for Harvard=E2=80=99s Portfolio Manager For Bill Ackman to call hi=
m to be like =E2=80=9Chey we are reshuffling the Bill Ackman Portfolio, do =
you want to buy any of it?=E2=80=9D I just don=E2=80=99t think that Harvard=
 really has a Portfolio Manager For Bill Ackman, and I think that its decis=
ion process is often less =E2=80=9Cdoes it make economic sense to sell this=
 concentrated stock position that someone walked in and handed to us=E2=80=
=9D and more =E2=80=9Cwhy=C2=A0<em>wouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>we sell this =
stuff and invest the money in something we picked?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there is also Ackman=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
call right,=E2=80=9D which is a little odd: Did he have the right to alloca=
te the excess above $15 million=C2=A0<em>if Harvard kept the stock and real=
ized that excess</em>, or was it just a standalone derivative contract wher=
e Harvard owed him any value of Coupang over $15 million whether or not it =
owned the stock? The latter seems weird, but Ackman seems to think that was=
 the spirit of the deal; he writes:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unfortunately, the stock sale issue has never =
been resolved and nearly three years have gone by. And it should not have b=
een hard for Harvard to resolve this problem. All Harvard has to do is hono=
r the agreement it had made with me.=C2=A0That is, to grant me the right I =
bargained for:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The right to allocate the $70m of excess proce=
eds to the Harvard-related initiative of my choice. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this should not be hard. Harvard has $50,0=
00,000,000 of assets, and Harvard's obligation to me represents only 0.14% =
of these funds, and the funds all stay at Harvard. =C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Put his name on a program in nonprofit portfol=
io management.</p>
