<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ross Stevens vs. Penn</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a trade:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are the founder, chief executive =
officer and main owner of some private company. Say it=E2=80=99s worth $1 b=
illion and you own 90%; your employees own the other 10%.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You would like to make a charitable donation, say =
to your alma mater. Instead of giving cash, you give some of the shares tha=
t you own in your company. Say you give the charity 10% of the company, wor=
th $100 million. Now you own 80%, the charity owns 10%, your employees own =
10%.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You take a $100=C2=A0million =
tax deduction, on your personal taxes: You gave the charity property worth =
$100 million, so you deduct that from your income for this year. That saves=
 you, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/336837=
79.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmVyZHdhbGxldC5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZS90YXhlcy9mZWRlcmFsL=
WluY29tZS10YXgtYnJhY2tldHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7515086a" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> $37=
=C2=A0million in taxes</a>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A week=
=C2=A0later, you change your mind. But the gift is already final.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But! Your=C2=A0<em>company=C2=A0</em>has an=
 interesting corporate charter. Until last week, the only owners of the com=
pany were you and your employees. What if they do something scandalous and =
you have to fire=C2=A0them? The company=E2=80=99s charter anticipates that =
possibility: It says that, if an employee is fired for cause =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0for breaking the law, for bringing disgrace on the company, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then their shares are forfeited. They just disappear: They don=E2=
=80=99t get paid out for those shares, they just lose them, and everyone el=
se owns a bit more of the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>What if you can fire <em>the charity </em>for cause? What if your alma mat=
er did something scandalous? Then you can take away their shares without pa=
ying them. The $100 million stake that the charity owned in your company ju=
st vanishes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because the charity=
=E2=80=99s 10% stake is canceled, you now own 88.9% of the company, and you=
r employees own 11.1%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But what about taxes?</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Arguably, by canceling the charity=E2=80=99s =
share of the company and effectively reallocating it (mostly) to yourself (=
and a little to your employees), you have income: The value of your stake i=
n the company increased by about $89 million, so you have $89 million of ta=
xable income. (And your employees have $11 million of taxable income, whoop=
s.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But=C2=A0<em>arguably=C2=A0<=
/em>there is no income. After all, you haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>gotten more=
 shares:=C2=A0</em>All that is happened is that some=C2=A0<em>other </em>ow=
ner=E2=80=99s shares were canceled. If I own stock in Amazon.com Inc., and =
Amazon buys back somebody else=E2=80=99s stock, my ownership interest in Am=
azon goes up, but I don=E2=80=99t report income or pay taxes. (If I donate =
$1 million of corporate stock to charity in 2023, and in 2024 the company g=
oes bankrupt and the shares become worthless, I still keep the 2023 tax ded=
uction.) Arguably something similar happened here: Someone else=E2=80=99s s=
hares were canceled, but you didn=E2=80=99t get any more shares, so you hav=
e no income, so you don=E2=80=99t pay any taxes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">So you donated $100 million of stock (Step 2), got a tax ded=
uction worth $37 million (Step 3), got=C2=A0<em>back=C2=A0</em>$89 million =
of stock (Step 7), and kept the tax deduction (Step 10). You are up $26 mil=
lion. Good trade!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Such a good trad=
e that you might go out and find some=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>charities to=
 give money to, charities that you think might=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>disa=
ppoint you, so you can do this again.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m kidding, I think. I don=E2=80=99t =
think this trade actually works, or that anyone would do it. But having spo=
tted a funny possible tax shelter, I feel obligated to mention it to you, t=
hough I feel far more obligated to tell you that (1) it is not legal or tax=
 advice and (2) in fact a tax lawyer I talked to was like =E2=80=9Cnah I do=
n=E2=80=99t think so.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> Still <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3368377=
9.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tLzIwMjMvMTIvMDcvdXBlbm4tYW50aXNlbWl0aX=
NtLW1hZ2lsbC0xMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1kb25hdGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB150352b1"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">here=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A University of Pennsylvania donor is withdraw=
ing a gift worth around $100 million to protest the school's response to an=
tisemitism on campus.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The big picture: The final straw for Ross Stev=
ens, founder and CEO of Stone Ridge Asset Management, was Tuesday's widely =
criticized congressional testimony by Penn president Liz Magill.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Details: The gift from Stevens, a Penn undergr=
ad alum, was given in December 2017 to help establish a center for innovati=
on in finance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was in the form of limited partnership unit=
s in Stone Ridge, with the current value estimated at around $100 million.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stevens, in a letter from his lawyers to Penn,=
 alleges that the school has violated the terms of the limited partnership =
agreement, including its anti-discrimination and anti-harassment policies.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s from Axios=E2=80=99s Dan Primac=
k last Thursday; since then, Magill has resigned and maybe Stevens is appea=
sed. I have no idea if he actually withdrew the gift,=C2=A0or will do it. B=
ut the bones of the trade are there. He is the founder and controlling owne=
r of Stone Ridge Holdings Group LP, which owns Stone Ridge Asset Management=
 and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.2583=
99/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3RvbmVyaWRnZWFtLmNvbS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB019b0f3=
0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">a few related financial businesses</a>. He donated some Stone =
Ridge limited partnership units to Penn; those units are =E2=80=9Cnow value=
d at approximately $100 million,=E2=80=9D Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s lawyers say=
 in a letter to Penn that Primack included with his story.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, well,=C2=A0<em>Stevens=C2=A0</em>did=
n=E2=80=99t ask for the units back; rather,=C2=A0<em>Stone Ridge=C2=A0</em>=
threatened to cancel them. The lawyers represent the firm, not Stevens hims=
elf. They write:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a holder of Stone Ridge Unit, the Universit=
y is bound by and must comply with the terms of Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s limit=
ed partner agreement (=E2=80=98LP Agreement=E2=80=99). Under that Agreement=
, Stone Ridge has the ability, in its sole discretion, to retire the Units =
of a limited partner that has engaged in conduct constituting =E2=80=9CLimi=
ted Partner Cause.=E2=80=9D (LP Agreement =C2=A7 10.12.) The LP Agreement d=
efines =E2=80=9CLimited Partner Cause=E2=80=9D broadly to include, as relev=
ant here, violations (by the limited partner) of laws or rules applicable t=
o Stone Ridge that are "materially injurious to [Stone Ridge's] business, r=
eputation, character or standing.=E2=80=9D (Id. =C2=A7 2.1.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the rules applicable to Stone Ridge are =
its own anti-discrimination and anti-harassment policies and the laws=C2=A0=
of New York State that prohibit workplace discrimination and harassment. Fo=
r example, Stone Ridge strict prohibits all forms of discrimination and har=
assment based on, among other things, religion. =E2=80=9CThis prohibition a=
pplies to physical conduct, verbal conduct (including taunting,=C2=A0jokes,=
 threats, epithets, derogatory comments or slurs based on an individual's p=
rotected status);=C2=A0and visual and/or written conduct {including derogat=
ory posters. photographs, calendars, cartoons, drawings, websites, email, t=
ext messages or gestures based on an indvidual=E2=80=99s protected status).=
 These policies, among others, were enacted by Stone Ridge to ensure a safe=
 and respectful environment or its employees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Stevens and Stone Ridge are appalled by th=
e University=E2=80=99s stance on antisemitism on campus. Its permissive app=
roach to hate speech calling for violence against Jews and laissez faire at=
titude toward harassment and discrimination against Jewish students would v=
iolate any policies of rules that prohibit harassment and discrimination ba=
sed on religion, including those of Stone Ridge. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In light of=
 the foregoing, Stone Ridge has reason to believe that the University=E2=80=
=99s actions (or lack thereof) constitute =E2=80=9CLimited Partner Cause=E2=
=80=9D under Section 10.12 of the LP Agreement, which gives Stone Ridge the=
 ability, in its sole discretion, to retire the University=E2=80=99s Units.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is an incredibly weird argument. The idea=
 of that =E2=80=9CLimited Partner Cause=E2=80=9D provision is surely, like,=
 if one of the employee-owners of Stone Ridge does sexual harassment and em=
barrasses the firm, he can be fired and his units confiscated. It is harder=
 to see how Penn violated any =E2=80=9Claws or rules applicable to Stone Ri=
dge,=E2=80=9D or could possibly have done so, or could possibly do somethin=
g =E2=80=9Cmaterially injurious to [Stone Ridge=E2=80=99s] business, reputa=
tion, character or standing.=E2=80=9D I assume the point here is to make a =
clever threat, not an argument that could stand up in court.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But never mind that! My point is just that whe=
n <em>Stevens </em>donated the units, he presumably could have taken a tax =
deduction, but if=C2=A0<em>Stone Ridge=C2=A0</em>takes them back, he maybe =
doesn=E2=80=99t need to reverse that deduction? Cool trade if so.</p>
