 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a> about how deals =
are typically negotiated by arguing about what terms are =E2=80=9Cmarket,=
=E2=80=9D that is, standard in deals of that type. One question is how you =
know what terms are market. I said:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You have to pay attention to what =
deals happen, and have someone summarize them, but with a bit of work you c=
an build a database, or even keep running track of all the deals in your he=
ad I guess.=C2=A0Or get yourself a large language model and ask it =E2=80=
=9Cwhat is a standard ordinary course of business covenant for a US public =
company merger these days?=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coincidentally also yesterday Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s Brian Baxter <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
33683779.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vYnVzaW5lc3MtYW5kLXB=
yYWN0aWNlL2V4LXdhY2h0ZWxsLWxhd3llci13ZXJ0bWFuLXNlY3VyZXMtNi1taWxsaW9uLWZvci=
