<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] I could argue this the other way. What is =
Ackman=E2=80=99s put worth? Well, let=E2=80=99s say you=E2=80=99re Harvard,=
 you have this Coupang stock, Ackman has promised to pay you the difference=
 if it goes below $10 million, and it goes to $0 =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s a s=
tartup, startups commonly fail, etc. You go to Ackman for the $10 million. =
One possibility is that he doesn=E2=80=99t have it: Whatever wiped out the =
value of Coupang also wiped out his fortune, leaving him too strapped to gi=
ve you the $10 million. This doesn=E2=80=99t seem that likely, but it's not=
 a zero probability. Another possibility is that he doesn=E2=80=99t want to=
 give it: Between his donation and Coupang=E2=80=99s fall, he has gotten ma=
d at Harvard for some reason, and no longer wants to make up the shortfall.=
 This has a higher probability! Ackman does have some problems with Harvard=
! (In either of these two cases, maybe you can sue him to enforce your arra=
ngement, but that is a bad look and I don=E2=80=99t know how enforceable it=
 is.) A third possibility is that he writes you the $10 million check, but =
in his own mind he deducts that $10 million from what he would have given t=
o Harvard anyway. You come to him at the end of the year saying =E2=80=9CHa=
rvard <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.258=
399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1JYk5kY2RPM19Hbw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBafd66635" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">could use an international airport</a>, coul=
d you chip in $10 million=E2=80=9D and he says =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, I already=
 wrote you a $10 million check this year, go away.=E2=80=9D The $10 million=
 is not necessarily *additive*. So you would not, ex ante, value this put a=
t its full Black-Scholes value; you would not be absolutely certain that th=
e stock plus the put will always be worth at least $10 million.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] That is, before, you owned 80 units, the c=
harity owned 10, the employees owned 10. Now the charity=E2=80=99s 10 units=
 are canceled, so you own 80 out of 90 units, and the employees own 10 out =
of 90. This is not the only way this contract could work, and my understand=
ing is that it is more common, in an investment firm's limited partnership =
agreement, for canceled shares to essentially be reallocated to the founder=
/CEO, meaning that in practice you=E2=80=99d end up back with 90% and the e=
mployees with 10%. But this mechanism is theoretically possible, and funnie=
r.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-5" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[5] Again, this leakage is not necessary, or e=
ven common (see previous footnote); you might just get all $100 million of =
the value.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-6" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[6] But with some doubt! Also, to be clear, I =
think the trade is pretty tricky if your company is a *partnership*, as Sto=
ne Ridge is. Then the reallocation of capital caused by the cancelation of =
another partner=E2=80=99s shares arguably is income to you. (The relevant c=
ase is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33683779.25=
8399/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNldGV4dC5jb20vY2FzZS9sZWhtYW4tdi1jb21tci1vZi1pbnRlcm5hbC=
1yZXZlbnVlLTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28431d8b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Lehman v. Commissi=
oner</a>.) But I think that if your company is a *corporation* you are in b=
etter shape; canceling shares of a corporation clearly *isn=E2=80=99t* inco=
me to the other shareholders. I think it is less common for a corporation t=
o have a cancelation-of-shares-for-cause provision, though not theoreticall=
y impossible, and I think there are other tax reasons why you wouldn=E2=80=
=99t want the company to be organized as a corporation, but still there=E2=
=80=99s maybe a fun trade there. This is incredibly not tax or legal advice=
.</p>
</div>
